<DOC><DOCNO> AP880513-0026 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0222EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-Edgars     05-13 0235</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Edgars,0248</SECOND><HEAD>Aaron Elkins Wins Edgar</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   ``Old Bones,'' a mystery novel set in France andreaching back to World War II, won the Edgar from the MysteryWriters of America for its writer Aaron Elkins.   Edgars, named for Edgar Allan Poe, were presented for bestmystery works of 1987 at a banquet Thursday night during theconvention of the International Congress of Crime Writers.   Angela Lansbury and Vincent Price received Raven awards, namedfor Poe's poem, for contributions to the world of mystery.   Novelist Phyllis Whitney was named Grand Master of Mystery forlifetime achievement.   Edgars also went to ``Stakeout'' by Jim Kouf as best mysterymovie; ``Nutcracker'' by William Hanley as best TV movie; ``TheMusgrave Ritual,'' starring Sherlock Holmes, by Jeremy Paul, in thePBS ``Mystery'' series, as best TV segment, and ``Bimbos of theDeath Sun'' by Sharyn McCrumb as best paperback original.   ``Death Among Strangers,'' by Deidre S. Laiken, was chosen bestfirst mystery; ``CBS Murders'' by Richard Hammer best fact crime;``Introduction to the Detective Story'' by Leroy Lad Panek bestcritical study; ``Soft Monkey'' by Harlan Ellison best short story,and ``Lucy Forever and Miss Rosetree, Shrinks'' by Susan Shrevebest juvenile mystery.   Editor Ruth Cavin received the Ellery Queen Award for lifetimeachievement.   Eric M. Heideman's ``Roger, Mr. Whilkie'' won the Robert FishAward for a short story.</TEXT></DOC>